title: Hundreds March in Manhattan to Protest the Death of Freddie Gray
description: The protest, which resulted in more than 60 arrests, was meant to show solidarity with demonstrators in Baltimore and to criticize the tactics of the police in both cities.

title: Baltimore Mayor Treads Fine Line in Divided City
description: Mayor Stephanie Rawlings-Blake must try to bring together two Baltimores, neither of which she is entirely a part: the gentrified city and the frustrated, low-income city.

title: Taking to the Baltimore Streets, but for Peace and Progress
description: In Baltimore, an array of pastors, politicians, community leaders and even gang members have repeatedly worked to calm crowds, effectively helping the police impose a curfew.

title: Baltimore Leaders Try to Curb Expectations Over a Pending Police Report
description: An edgy peace held as a crowd took to the streets Wednesday night, and the mayor and police sought to tamp down expectations that residents would learn details soon about how a young black man died.

title: Trying to Locate the Living, Nepal Rescuers Find Only Frustration
description: Residents of Bhaktapur told a search-and-rescue team that had traveled from Fairfax County, Va., that there was no one left to save in their shattered city after Saturday’s earthquake.

title: Obama Administration Steps Back From Effort to End Federal Death Penalty
description: The obstacles the Obama administration faced in ending the federal death penalty provide vivid examples of just how politically fraught the debate remains.

title: Health Problems Take Root in a West Baltimore Neighborhood That Is Sick of Neglect
description: In Upton-Druid Heights — one of Baltimore’s poorest neighborhoods and the scene of some of its most vocal protests — residents die from nearly every major disease at substantially higher rates than the city as a whole.

title: Hue Journal: Economic Boom Poses a New Threat, Among Many, to a Vietnamese Heritage
description: What weather, war and ideology have not yet undone to the character of the central Vietnamese city of Hue, development may.

title: U2’s Flight to Now (Turbulence Included)
description: After trouble on the runway, the band’s “Innocence and Experience” tour is taking off.

title: New York Plan to Save Energy May Mean a Dimmer Skyline
description: Mayor Bill de Blasio’s administration and a host of environmental advocates agree that light pollution should be addressed, but some are disputing parts of a proposed City Council bill.

title: A Saudi Royal Shake-Up With a Goal of Stability
description: With Saudi Arabia locked in proxy wars with Iran, King Salman put the two princes most responsible for the kingdom’s security into the line of succession.

title: A Founder of Secret, the Anonymous Social App, Is Shutting It Down
description: Secret’s rapid rise and fall illustrates the flash-in-the-pan nature of Silicon Valley’s current technology boom.

title: Shinzo Abe of Japan Avoids Specifics in Speech on Trade Accord
description: In the first address by a Japanese prime minister to a joint meeting of Congress, Shinzo Abe appealed to skeptical American lawmakers to back a Pacific trade accord.

title: ArtsBeat: Charlie Hebdo Cartoonist to Stop Drawing Muhammed
description: Muhammad “no longer interests me,” Rénald Luzier, who works under the name Luz, said in an interview.

title: New York City Underreported School Violence to State, Audit Shows
description: An examination by the state comptroller of 10 schools found that almost a third of the violent episodes were not reported, as required.

title: Seen ‘Hamilton’? No? You Poor Thing.
description: Celebrities are flocking to see the hip-hop musical “Hamilton” at the cozy Public Theater, setting off a mad status grab.

title: Jean Nidetch, 91, Dies; 72 Pounds Lighter, She Helped Start Weight Watchers
description: A 214-pound Queens housewife struggled with a lifelong addiction to food until she shed 72 pounds and became the public face of the worldwide weight-control empire Weight Watchers.

title: Canadian Partnership Shielded Identities of Donors to Clinton Foundation
description: The foundation says that the partnership is not bound by an agreement that Hillary Rodham Clinton signed to make all donors public while she led the State Department, and that under Canadian law, contributors’ names cannot be made public.

title: First Draft: Hillary Clinton to Jump Start Fund-Raising Efforts
description: Hillary Rodham Clinton had once planned to wait until May to hold her first fund-raising events. But in the last two weeks, she has moved up her schedule, according to donors and people in contact with the campaign.

title: Supreme Court Upholds Limit on Judicial Fund-Raising
description: The justices said it was permissible for states to forbid judicial candidates to personally ask supporters for money.
